<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-651-472  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 651 472.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  July 16 1990 v4 n27 p25(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Image processing: fed users focus on enhancing, manipulatingpictures.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rivenbark, Leigh.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Image processing allows federal agencies to improve images frommicroscopes and satellites for medical and geological research.andO;Image processing enhances images to provide more detail than thehuman eye can reveal.andP;  Most image processing is done by highlysophisticated hardware, but software is not as well developed, andmost of those written for government scientific applications arewritten by users themselves.andP;  At the National Institutes ofHealth, 35 facilities study a wide range of medical issues usingimage processing, which can correct for alterations in the studiedsubject in addition to improving picture quality.andP;  The USGeological Survey's Earth Resources Observing Satellite DataCenter uses image processing to correct for rotation and curvatureof the earth, and to remove clouds from pictures by processingmultiple images.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Image ProcessingMedical ResearchGeologyNew TechniqueComputer VisionUser-Written SoftwareApplicationsUnited States. National Institutes of HealthUnited States. Geological Survey.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>